I"%<div style="background-color: #E3F4F4; padding: 15px 15px 15px 15px; border:1px solid black;">
  <b>[Cut Property] If \(A\) and \(B\) are nonempty, disjoint sets with \(A \cup B = \mathbf{R}\) and \(a &lt; b\) for all \(a \in A\) and \(b \in B\), then there exists \(c \in \mathbf{R}\) such that \(x \leq c\) whenever \(x \in A\) and \(x \geq c\) whenever \(x \in B\).</b>
</div>
<p><br />
For the definitions of an upper bound and the least upper bound of a set. See <a href="https://strncat.github.io/jekyll/update/2024/05/03/analysis-set-bounded.html">This</a>.
<br />
<br /></p>
<h3>Proof:</h3>
<p>Let \(A\) and \(B\) be nonempty sets such that \(A \cup B = \mathbf{R}\). Since for all (a \in A) and (b \in B), we have (a &lt; b),</p>

<div>
$$
\begin{align*}
x \geq s \geq a.
\end{align*}
$$
</div>
<p>We also know that for any \(b \in B\), we must have \(t \geq b\). But we’re also given that \(t &gt; s\) so</p>
<div>
$$
\begin{align*}
t \geq b.
\end{align*}
$$
</div>
<p>We’re also given</p>

<p>\(\blacksquare\)
<br />
<br />
